<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    
    <title>get element by id</title>
</head>
<body>
   <h1 id="myheading">Hello World</h1>
   <button onclick="handlechange()"> Change Heading</button> 


  //javascript.........................................................
   <script>
    function handlechange(){
        
        var headingElement=document.getElementById("myheading");
        headingElement.textContent="New Heading Text";
    }
   </script>
</body>
</html>






     <!DOCTYPE html>: This is the document type declaration and specifies that the document is an HTML5 document.
<html lang="en">: This opening tag signifies the beginning of the HTML document, with "en" indicating that the language is English.
<head>: This section contains metadata about the document, like the title of the page, links to external resources, etc.
<title>get element by id</title>: Sets the title of the web page, which is usually displayed in the browser's title bar or tab.
</head>: Closes the head section of the document.
<body>: This is the main content area of the web page where the visible content is placed.
<h1 id="myheading">Hello World</h1>: This is an HTML heading element (<h1>) with the text "Hello World". 
     The id attribute is set to "myheading". The id attribute provides a unique identifier for the element, which can be used to manipulate it in JavaScript.
<button onclick="handlechange()"> Change Heading</button>: This is a button element that displays the text "Change Heading". 
     The onclick attribute specifies a JavaScript function (handlechange()) to be executed when the button is clicked.










     <script>: This tag is used to embed JavaScript code within the HTML document.
function handlechange(){ ... }: This defines a JavaScript function named handlechange. This function is called when the button is clicked.
var headingElement = document.getElementById("myheading");: This line retrieves the HTML element with the id "myheading". 
  The document.getElementById() method is used to get a reference to an HTML element by its id.
headingElement.textContent = "New Heading Text";: This line updates the text content of the selected heading element. It sets the text content to "New Heading Text".
The overall functionality of the code is that when the button labeled "Change Heading" is clicked, it triggers the handlechange() function.
  This function finds the <h1> element with the id "myheading" and changes its text content to "New Heading Text".
